05640nam a22008055i 9780812206043DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20112009pau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979754112  a97808122060437 a10.9783/97808122060432doi  a(DE-B1597)449444  a(OCoLC)794929407  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aPOL0110102bisacsh04a957.7044/311 aAnderson, Liam, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCrisis in Kirkuk :bThe Ethnopolitics of Conflict and Compromise /cGareth Stansfield, Liam Anderson. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2011] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (312 p.) :b20 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aNational and Ethnic Conflict in the 21st Century00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction -- tPart I. Kirkuk and Its Environs -- tChapter 1. Kirkuk before Iraq -- tChapter 2. Kirkuk in the Twentieth Century -- tPart II. Three Ethnopolitical Perspectives -- tChapter 3. The Post-2003 Iraqi Context -- tChapter 4. The Turkmen Perspective The Demise of a Formerly Dominant Community -- tChapter 5. The Kurdish Perspective Gaining ‘‘Jerusalem’’ -- tChapter 6. The Arab Perspective Applying the Old Rules -- tPart III. The Postwar Struggle for Kirkuk -- tChapter 7. The Kurds Ascendant -- tChapter 8. The Kurds Triumphant -- tChapter 9. The Kurds Denied -- tPart IV. The Future of Kirkuk Dimensions of Compromise -- tChapter 10. The Struggle for Kirkuk: Problems of Process -- tChapter 11. The Struggle for Kirkuk Problems of Final Status -- tChapter 12. The Struggle for Kirkuk Future Governance -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tPeople Interviewed -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDespite dramatic improvements in the security environment in most parts of Iraq, still unresolved are many core political issues, foremost of which is the conflict over the city and region of Kirkuk. With immense oil reserves and a diverse population of Kurds, Arabs, and Turkmens, Kirkuk in recent history has been scarred by interethnic violence and state-sponsored ethnic cleansing. Throughout the twentieth century, successive Arab Iraqi governments engaged in a brutal campaign to increase Kirkuk's Arab population at the expense of Kurds and Turkmens. Following the invasion of Iraq in 2003, a newly empowered Kurdish leadership has sought to reverse the effects of the Arabization campaign and to hold a referendum on incorporating Kirkuk into the Kurdistan Region. The Kurds' efforts are, however, strongly opposed by Kirkuk's Turkmens, Arabs, and also most states in the region.In Crisis in Kirkuk, Liam Anderson and Gareth Stansfield offer a dispassionate analysis of one of Iraq's most pressing and unresolved problems. Drawing on extensive research and fieldwork, the authors investigate the claims to ownership made by each of Kirkuk's competing communities. They consider the constitutional mechanisms put in place to address the issue and the problems that have plagued their implementation. The book concludes with an assessment of the measures needed to resolve the crisis in Kirkuk, stressing that finding a compromise acceptable to all sides is vital to the future stability of Iraq.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 4aMiddle Eastern. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / International Relations / Diplomacy.2bisacsh  aAfrican Studies.  aAsian Studies.  aMiddle Eastern Studies.  aPolitical Science.  aPublic Policy.1 aStansfield, Gareth, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package Complete Collectionz978311041345808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe Gru